  <h3>4. Mobile UX Design for Voice Search – Tap Targets, Font Sizes, and Thumb Zones</h3>
  <p>Speed is not enough. Your mobile site must be <strong>usable</strong> – especially for users who just used voice search and are now on your site expecting to take action.</p>

  <h4>4.1 Tap Targets Must Be at Least 48x48 Pixels</h4>
  <p>Google’s mobile usability guidelines require buttons and links to be large enough for a finger. Check your site: Are your “Call Now” and “Get Directions” buttons easy to tap without zooming? Increase padding. Example CSS: `button { padding: 12px 24px; }`.</p>
  
  <h4>4.2 Font Size Minimum 16px for Body Text</h4>
  <p>If your body text is smaller than 16px on mobile, users will pinch‑to‑zoom – a sign of bad UX. Google’s algorithm detects this. Set `body { font-size: 16px; }` and adjust headings proportionally.</p>
  
  <h4>4.3 Place Important CTAs Within Thumb Reach</h4>
  <p>Studies show that 75% of mobile users operate their phone with one thumb. The “thumb zone” is the bottom half of the screen. Put your phone number, WhatsApp link, and “Request Audit” button where the thumb naturally rests – not at the top.</p>
  
  <h4>4.4 Avoid Popups That Cover Content</h4>
  <p>Intrusive interstitials (popups that block main content) are penalized by Google, especially on mobile. If you must use a popup, make it small, dismissible, and triggered by exit intent – never on immediate load.</p>
  
  <h4>4.5 Click‑to‑Call Links Are Mandatory</h4>
  <p>For voice search users, the next step is often a phone call. Ensure every phone number on your mobile site is a `tel:` link. Example: `<a href="tel:+254710346425">Call us now</a>`. When tapped on mobile, it opens the dialer directly.</p>

  <h3>5. Testing Your Mobile Optimization – Free Tools You Can Use Today</h3>
  <p>You cannot improve what you do not measure. Bookmark these free testing tools and run them monthly.</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Google PageSpeed Insights</strong> – gives Core Web Vitals data and specific fixes.</li>
    <li><strong>Google Mobile-Friendly Test</strong> (search.google.com/test/mobile-friendly) – tells you if Google considers your site mobile‑friendly.</li>
    <li><strong>WebPageTest.org</strong> – advanced testing; choose “Mobile” and location “Africa” to simulate Kenyan network conditions.</li>
    <li><strong>Chrome DevTools (F12) → Lighthouse tab</strong> – runs performance, accessibility, SEO audits right in your browser.</li>
    <li><strong>GTmetrix</strong> – gives waterfall charts showing exactly which element slows your page.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>6. Common Mobile Optimization Mistakes Kenyan Businesses Make (And How to Fix Them)</h3>
  
  <p><strong>❌ Mistake 1: Using non‑responsive themes/templates.</strong><br>Fix: If your site does not shrink and rearrange on phone, you need a responsive design. For static sites, add `<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">` (you already have it – good). Then test by resizing your browser window.</p>
  
  <p><strong>❌ Mistake 2: Hosting images on slow external servers.</strong><br>Fix: Upload images directly to your own hosting. Avoid hotlinking from free image sites.</p>
  
  <p><strong>❌ Mistake 3: Blocking JavaScript, CSS, or images in robots.txt.</strong><br>Fix: Googlebot needs access to all resources to properly render your mobile page. Check your `robots.txt` file.</p>
  
  <p><strong>❌ Mistake 4: Using Flash or outdated plugins.</strong><br>Fix: Flash does not work on most mobile browsers. Replace any Flash elements with HTML5 or plain images.</p>
  
  <p><strong>❌ Mistake 5: Forgetting about horizontal scrolling.</strong><br>Fix: Ensure no element has a fixed width larger than the viewport. Test by setting browser width to 320px.</p>

  <h3>7. How Google’s Mobile‑First Indexing Affects Voice Search in Kenya</h3>
  <p>Since 2019, Google has used the <strong>mobile version</strong> of your site for indexing and ranking – even for desktop searches. That means if your mobile site is missing content (e.g., you hide certain paragraphs or images on mobile), Google will act as if that content does not exist at all.</p>
  <p>For voice search, which is mobile‑dominant, mobile‑first indexing is even more critical. Ensure that <strong>all your conversational keywords, FAQ content, and schema markup are present on the mobile version</strong> – not hidden behind “Read more” links or accordions that require extra taps. Googlebot can click accordions, but it is not guaranteed to see hidden content as quickly.</p>
  <p><strong>Best practice:</strong> Show your main FAQs and key voice‑optimized content in plain HTML, not hidden by default. If you need to use accordions (for design), ensure the content is loaded in the DOM at page load (not lazy‑loaded).</p>

