  <h3>8. Common FAQ Schema Mistakes (And How to Avoid Them)</h3>
  <p>Google’s guidelines for FAQ schema are strict. Avoid these errors:</p>
  
  <p><strong>❌ Mistake 1: Using FAQ schema for promotional content.</strong><br>Each answer must genuinely answer the question. Do not stuff keywords or write a sales pitch. Google may issue a manual action (penalty) for “misleading structured data”.</p>
  
  <p><strong>❌ Mistake 2: Leaving answers empty or too short.</strong><br>Answers must be substantive. “Call us for more info” is not an answer. Write a helpful response first, then add a call to action.</p>
  
  <p><strong>❌ Mistake 3: Duplicating the same question across multiple pages with same schema.</strong><br>If you have multiple pages with identical FAQ schema, Google may ignore all of them. Keep unique questions per page.</p>
  
  <p><strong>❌ Mistake 4: Forgetting to update schema when content changes.</strong><br>If you edit an answer in the visible HTML but not in the JSON‑LD, Google sees a mismatch. Always update both.</p>
  
  <p><strong>❌ Mistake 5: Using FAQ schema on pages that are not FAQ pages.</strong><br>Google’s guidelines state that FAQ schema should be used only on pages that are primarily FAQ pages – not on product pages or blog posts. For product pages, use Product schema. For blog posts, use BlogPosting schema.</p>

