  <h2 style="border-left: 5px solid #f39c12; padding-left: 20px;">📍 Local SEO Signals: The Secret to Winning “Near Me” Voice Searches in Kenya</h2>
  
  <p>Voice search is inherently local. When someone asks, “Where can I get the best pizza near me?” or “Which hardware store is open on Sunday near Westlands?”, Google must decide which business to recommend. The decision is based on <strong>local SEO signals</strong> – your Google Business Profile, citations (mentions of your business on other websites), online reviews, and location‑optimized content.</p>
  
  <p>In Kenya, the “near me” voice search volume has grown <strong>210% in Nairobi</strong> over the past two years (source: Google Think with Kenya, 2026). That means tens of thousands of potential customers every month are actively looking for businesses like yours – using their voice. If your local signals are weak, Google will send those customers to your competitors.</p>
  
  <div style="background: #fff3e0; padding: 20px; border-radius: 16px; margin: 25px 0; border-left: 6px solid #f39c12;">
    <p style="font-weight: bold; margin-bottom: 8px;">📍 Key Stat to Remember:</p>
    <p>Google’s local search algorithm (often called the “Local Pack”) uses <strong>3 main factors</strong>: Relevance (does your business match the query?), Distance (are you near the searcher?), and Prominence (how well‑known are you?). Voice search relies on the same factors, but <strong>distance and prominence matter even more</strong> because voice answers are often just one result – not a list of three.</p>
