  <h3>1. Google Business Profile: Your #1 Local Voice Search Asset</h3>
  <p>Your <strong>Google Business Profile (GBP)</strong> – formerly Google My Business – is the single most important local SEO factor. When Google answers a “near me” voice query, it pulls data directly from GBP listings. If your profile is incomplete, unverified, or inaccurate, you will never appear in voice results – no matter how good your website is.</p>
  
  <h4>1.1 Claim and Verify Your GBP (If You Haven’t Already)</h4>
  <p>Go to <strong>business.google.com</strong>. Search for your business. If it exists, claim it. If not, create a new listing. Google will send a postcard with a verification code to your physical address (takes 5‑14 days in Kenya). Do not skip this step – unverified listings are invisible to voice search.</p>
  
  <h4>1.2 Complete EVERY Section (The Voice Search Checklist)</h4>
  <p>Google’s own data shows that <strong>fully completed GBP listings are 2.7x more likely to be considered trustworthy</strong> by the algorithm. Here is what you must fill out:</p>
  
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Business name:</strong> Use your real business name. Do not add keywords (“Best Plumber Nairobi” is a violation and can get you suspended).</li>
    <li><strong>Address:</strong> Exact physical address. If you serve customers at their location (e.g., plumber, electrician), you can set a service area instead. For voice search, a service area with specific neighborhoods works well.</li>
    <li><strong>Phone number:</strong> Use a local Kenyan number (e.g., 0710xxxxxx). Google prefers numbers with the same area code as your location. <strong>Important:</strong> Ensure this number is click‑to‑call on mobile.</li>
    <li><strong>Website URL:</strong> Link to your website. Make sure the URL is the same as the one you use elsewhere (consistency matters).</li>
    <li><strong>Categories:</strong> Choose the <strong>most specific primary category</strong> possible. Instead of “Restaurant”, choose “Nyama Choma Restaurant” or “Fast Food Restaurant”. Instead of “Plumber”, choose “Emergency Plumber” or “Water Heater Installation Service”.</li>
    <li><strong>Attributes:</strong> These are like “Open 24 hours”, “Women‑led”, “Outdoor seating”, “Free Wi‑Fi”. Voice search answers often include attributes (“find a restaurant with outdoor seating near me”). Add every relevant attribute.</li>
    <li><strong>Opening hours:</strong> Update for weekdays, weekends, and public holidays. If you are closed on certain days, say so. Voice search penalties apply for showing “open” when you are closed.</li>
    <li><strong>Products and services:</strong> List up to 10 products or services with descriptions. Use conversational language. Example: “Emergency plumbing repair – 24/7 service in Kilimani, Westlands, and Langata.”</li>
    <li><strong>Posts (Updates):</strong> Google Posts appear in your GBP listing. Voice search may pull fresh posts. Post at least weekly – special offers, new services, holiday hours.</li>
    <li><strong>Photos and videos:</strong> Listings with photos get 42% more requests for directions. Add at least 10 high‑quality images of your storefront, team, products, and work in progress.</li>
    <li><strong>Q&A section:</strong> Users (and you) can ask and answer questions. This is a goldmine for voice keywords. Proactively add 5‑10 common questions with concise answers. These answers sometimes appear in voice results.</li>
  </ul>
  
