  <h3>1. What Is a Featured Snippet? (And How Google Uses It for Voice)</h3>
  <p>A featured snippet (also called “position zero”) is the highlighted answer box that appears at the top of Google search results. It can take several forms:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Paragraph snippet:</strong> A block of text answering a “why”, “how”, or “what” question.</li>
    <li><strong>List snippet (bulleted or numbered):</strong> For steps, rankings, or ingredients.</li>
    <li><strong>Table snippet:</strong> For comparative data (prices, features, sizes).</li>
    <li><strong>Video snippet:</strong> A YouTube video thumbnail with a timestamp answer.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>For voice search, <strong>paragraph and list snippets</strong> are most commonly read aloud. Google’s algorithm selects the snippet it deems most authoritative, concise, and relevant. Then, when a user asks a matching voice query, Google Assistant reads that snippet verbatim – often including attribution to your business name.</p>
  
  <p>Imagine a potential customer asking, “Which digital marketing agency in Nairobi has the best reviews?” If your featured snippet answers that clearly and includes your business name, Google will say: <em>“According to DK Digital SEO, we have a 4.9 star rating from 36 reviews and specialize in voice search and local SEO.”</em> That is free, high‑trust advertising delivered directly to a ready buyer.</p>

  <h3>2. Types of Featured Snippets That Trigger Voice Search (With Kenyan Examples)</h3>
  
