  <h3>3. Step‑by‑Step: How to Find Featured Snippet Opportunities in Kenya</h3>
  <p>You do not need expensive tools. Follow these free methods to find questions that already have snippets – or that are missing snippets (even better).</p>
  
  <h4>Step 1: Use Google’s “People Also Ask” (PAA) Boxes</h4>
  <p>Search for a broad keyword related to your business (e.g., “SEO services Kenya”). Scroll to the PAA box. Each question is a potential snippet target. Click a question – more questions appear. Keep expanding. Within 10 minutes, you will have 50+ question opportunities.</p>
  <p><strong>Pro tip:</strong> Use the free tool <strong>AlsoAsked.com</strong> to visualize the entire PAA tree without clicking manually.</p>
  
  <h4>Step 2: Look for Keywords Where No Snippet Exists (Low‑Hanging Fruit)</h4>
  <p>Search for a question like “How much does a plumber charge per hour in Nairobi?”. Scroll to the top of results. If there is <strong>no</strong> featured snippet box, that is a golden opportunity. The snippet is “up for grabs”. Create a page that answers that question clearly, and you have a high chance of winning the snippet within weeks.</p>
  
  <h4>Step 3: Analyze Competitor Snippets You Can Improve</h4>
  <p>If a snippet exists, see if you can create a <strong>better answer</strong>. “Better” means:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>More concise (shorter paragraphs).</li>
    <li>More up‑to‑date (include 2026 data).</li>
    <li>More local (mention specific Kenyan prices, laws, or examples).</li>
    <li>Better formatted (bullet points, bold key phrases).</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Google’s algorithm periodically tests new snippets. If your content is clearly superior, you can replace the existing snippet.</p>
  
  <h4>Step 4: Use Search Console to Find Your Own Snippet Opportunities</h4>
  <p>In Google Search Console, go to Performance → Queries. Filter for queries where your average position is between 4 and 10. These are pages that rank on page one but not yet in position zero. Add better structured answers to those pages – you are only a few spots away from the snippet.</p>
  
  <h4>Step 5: Target Question Keywords Directly</h4>
  <p>Create content that explicitly targets question keywords. Use headings like:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>&lt;h2&gt;How to find the best electrician in Nairobi?&lt;/h2&gt;</li>
    <li>&lt;h2&gt;What is the cost of a website in Kenya?&lt;/h2&gt;</li>
    <li>&lt;h2&gt;Why do I need voice search SEO for my business?&lt;/h2&gt;</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Then immediately answer the question in the following paragraph (40-60 words).</p>

  <h3>4. How to Structure Your Content to Win Featured Snippets (Voice‑Ready Formatting)</h3>
  <p>Winning a snippet is not magic – it follows predictable patterns. Apply these formatting rules to every page you want to optimize for voice.</p>
  
  <h4>4.1 Answer the Question Immediately (Within 100 Characters)</h4>
  <p>Do not bury the answer. Start your paragraph with the direct answer, then add supporting details. Example:</p>
  <p><strong>Bad (voice‑unfriendly):</strong> “There are many factors that affect the cost of SEO in Kenya, including the size of your website, the number of keywords, and the experience of the agency. Generally speaking, you can expect to pay anywhere from…”</p>
  <p><strong>Good (voice‑ready):</strong> “SEO in Kenya costs between $200 and $500 per month for most small businesses. This includes keyword research, on‑page optimization, and monthly reporting. Prices vary based on competition and website size.”</p>
  <p>The first sentence of the good example could be read aloud as a complete answer.</p>
  
  <h4>4.2 Keep Paragraphs Short (2-3 Sentences Maximum)</h4>
  <p>Google prefers short paragraphs for snippets. Break long paragraphs into multiple short ones. Voice assistants need clear start and end points.</p>
  
  <h4>4.3 Use Bullet Points and Numbered Lists Generously</h4>
  <p>For questions asking for steps (“how to”), use an ordered list (`<ol>`). For features or benefits, use unordered lists (`<ul>`). Label lists clearly. Example:</p>
  <pre style="background: #1e293b; color: #e2e8f0; padding: 15px; border-radius: 12px; overflow-x: auto; font-size: 0.8rem;">
&lt;h2&gt;What documents do I need to apply for a Kenyan passport?&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Original birth certificate and a copy&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;National ID card (original and copy)&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Passport photos (2, white background)&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Application fee receipt (KES 4,550)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
  </pre>
  
  <h4>4.4 Use Tables for Comparisons</h4>
  <p>If your question involves comparing prices, features, or options, a table is often chosen as the snippet. Use `<table>` with clear headers. Example: compare SEO packages by price and deliverables.</p>
  
  <h4>4.5 Bold the Key Answer Phrase</h4>
  <p>Use `<strong>` or `<b>` to highlight the exact phrase that answers the question. Google may prioritize bolded text. Example: “<strong>SEO in Kenya costs between $200 and $500 per month</strong> for most small businesses.”</p>
  
  <h4>4.6 Add a “Definition” or “Summary” Box</h4>
  <p>At the beginning of your page or section, add a short summary box (styled with a background color) that answers the main question in 1-2 sentences. Google sometimes pulls from these boxes directly.</p>

