  <h3>7. Measuring and Tracking Your Featured Snippet Wins</h3>
  <p>Google Search Console does not directly show “featured snippet” as a metric, but you can infer it.</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Check average position for specific queries.</strong> A position of “1” with a high click‑through rate (CTR) often indicates a featured snippet. Snippets typically have CTR between 20‑40% for informational queries.</li>
    <li><strong>Use the “Performance” report with the “Search appearance” filter.</strong> In GSC, select “Search appearance” → “Featured snippet” to see which queries triggered your snippets. Not all data is shown, but it gives a baseline.</li>
    <li><strong>Manually check your top question keywords weekly.</strong> Search for 5‑10 key voice queries in incognito mode. Note if your site appears in the snippet box. Screenshot for your records.</li>
    <li><strong>Track voice call conversions.</strong> Train your receptionist to ask, “How did you find us?” If the customer says “Google voice search” or “I asked my phone”, that is a snippet win.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>8. Advanced: Using “HowTo” Schema to Win Voice Snippets for Procedural Queries</h3>
  <p>For “how to” queries (e.g., “How to change a tire in Kenya”, “How to apply for an e‑visa”), Google sometimes prefers <strong>HowTo schema</strong> over standard FAQ schema. HowTo schema explicitly marks up step‑by‑step instructions.</p>
  
