  <h3>8. Testing and Validating Your Schema (Free Tools)</h3>
  <p>One typo in your JSON can break the entire schema, and Google will ignore it. Always test before publishing.</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Google Rich Results Test:</strong> search.google.com/test/rich-results – paste your URL or HTML code. Shows which schema types are detected and any errors.</li>
    <li><strong>Schema.org Validator:</strong> validator.schema.org – strict validation, good for catching subtle issues.</li>
    <li><strong>JSONLint.com:</strong> validates JSON syntax (missing commas, brackets).</li>
    <li><strong>Google Search Console:</strong> After deployment, check “Enhancements” reports for errors or warnings.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h4>8.1 Common Schema Errors (And How to Fix)</h4>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Missing @context or @type:</strong> Every schema block must start with `"@context": "https://schema.org"` and `"@type": "Something"`.</li>
    <li><strong>Invalid date formats:</strong> Use ISO 8601: `2026-06-12` for dates, `2026-06-12T09:00:00+03:00` for times with timezone.</li>
    <li><strong>Missing required fields:</strong> For Product, `name` and `offers` are required. For Event, `name`, `startDate`, `location` are required.</li>
    <li><strong>Using relative URLs:</strong> Always use absolute URLs (`https://dkdigitalseo.online/page`) not relative (`/page`).</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>9. Schema Maintenance – Keep Your Structured Data Fresh for Voice Search</h3>
  <p>Voice search penalizes outdated information. If your Product schema shows a price of KES 10,000 but your actual price is KES 12,000, Google may suppress your listing after detecting inconsistency. Follow this maintenance schedule:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Weekly:</strong> For e-commerce, update `price` and `availability` in Product schema whenever inventory changes.</li>
    <li><strong>Monthly:</strong> Re‑test your top 10 pages with Google Rich Results Tool. Look for any warnings.</li>
    <li><strong>Quarterly:</strong> Review `priceValidUntil` and `eventStatus` – remove expired events, update prices.</li>
    <li><strong>After site redesign:</strong> Ensure schema code was not accidentally deleted. Many redesigns strip JSON‑LD blocks.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p><strong>Automation tip:</strong> If you use WordPress, plugins like <strong>Rank Math SEO</strong> or <strong>Schema Pro</strong> automatically generate and update schema for products, posts, and events. For static HTML sites (like yours), you may need to manually update, but you can use a CMS or a simple script to inject JSON‑LD dynamically.</p>

