    <li><strong>Queries in YouTube Search that are conversational</strong> (e.g., “how do I fix a leaking pipe” rather than “plumbing repair”).</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p>In YouTube Studio → Analytics → Reach → “Google search terms”, look for long, question‑based phrases. These are your voice wins. Note the position and impressions.</p>
  
  <p>For self‑hosted videos, use Google Search Console: filter by “Video” appearance. This shows queries where your video rich result appeared – many of which are voice‑triggered.</p>

  <h3>9. Common Video Voice Search Mistakes</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>❌ No transcript or auto‑captions only.</strong> Google cannot “hear” your video; it reads the transcript. Without a custom transcript, your video is invisible for voice.</li>
    <li><strong>❌ Videos that are too long without chapters.</strong> A 30‑minute tutorial with no timestamps will never be used for voice. Break it into chapters or create shorter videos.</li>
    <li><strong>❌ Titles that don’t match voice queries.</strong> A title like “Tutorial 101” won’t trigger voice. Use natural language.</li>
    <li><strong>❌ Embedding videos without schema.</strong> For self‑hosted videos, no schema = no voice eligibility.</li>
    <li><strong>❌ Ignoring “show me” queries.</strong> These are growing fast. Create content specifically for them.</li>
  </ul>

